  "response": "The number of pictures a 2GB SD card can hold depends on several factors, including the resolution and file size of the images, as well as the level of compression. Here's a rough estimate based on common scenarios:\n\n1. **12 Megapixel JPEG (High Quality, ~4MB per photo):**\n   - **2GB = 2000MB**\n   - **2000MB / 4MB = 500 photos**\n\n2. **8 Megapixel JPEG (Good Quality, ~2.5MB per photo):**\n   - **2000MB / 2.5MB = 800 photos**\n\n3. **5 Megapixel JPEG (Average Quality, ~1.5MB per photo):**\n   - **2000MB / 1.5MB \u2248 1333 photos**\n\n4. **RAW Format (Uncompressed, ~30MB per photo):**\n   - **2000MB / 30MB \u2248 66 photos**\n\nKeep in mind that these are approximations, as file sizes can vary depending on the camera settings, subject matter, and compression algorithms. If you're shooting in RAW or high-resolution JPEG, you'll store fewer photos, while lower-quality JPEGs will allow for more.",
